<div class="da-review customer-review">

 <div class="review-header">
  <div class="review-meta">
   <h5>
    <span class="customerReviewTitle">Poor emoji support</span>
    <div class='rating' role='img' tabindex='-1' aria-label='1 star'><div><span class="rating-star">&nbsp;</span><span class="rating-star ghost">&nbsp;</span><span class="rating-star ghost">&nbsp;</span><span class="rating-star ghost">&nbsp;</span><span class="rating-star ghost">&nbsp;</span></div></div>

   </h5>
   <span class="user-info">by
    <a href='https://itunes.apple.com/WebObjects/MZStore.woa/wa/viewUsersUserReviews?userProfileId=21755350' class="reviewer">Nella2577</a>
     -
     Version
     2.8.0
    
    -
    Sep 13, 2017
   </span>
  </div>
  <div class="review-see-all">
   <a href='https://itunes.apple.com/WebObjects/MZStore.woa/wa/viewUsersUserReviews?userProfileId=21755350' class="see-all">
   All Reviews by This User
   </a>
  </div>
 </div>
 <p class="content" data-text-truncate-lines="6">
  Doesn‚Äôt support the latest emoji. And using the system emoji menu (ctrl+cmd+space) to input the emoji results in poor handling of unicode characters because it decomposes modifiers. When I sent a request to their support team, they responded with:<br/><br/>&quot;When these emoji are included in Slack messages from iOS or macOS devices that support the newer emoji, they may show up as a base emoji plus gender identifier, or as a little blank square. This is obviously not ideal, and while I can't guarantee **when or if** Slack will support the newer emoji and emoji variations, it is something that we're looking in to and hope to include in a future update.‚Äù (emphasis mine)<br/><br/>Glad to see you guys are trying your hardest ü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
 </p>
 
 
  <div class="developer-response">
    <span class="developer-info">
        <span class="developer-response-title">Developer Response</span>
        -
        Sep 15, 2017
    </span>
      <p><span></span></p>
   <span class="developer-response-body">
        <p class="content" data-text-truncate-lines="2">
            We're definitely working on adding support for newer emoji sets. We're sorry it's taking a while, and we really appreciate this feedback.
        </p>
    </span>
   </div>
 
 
